//dom in javascript
// DOM stands for Document Object Model. It is a programming interface for web documents. 
// It represents the structure of a document as a tree of objects, where each object corresponds to a part of the document, such as an element, attribute, or text node. 
// The DOM allows developers to manipulate the content and structure of a web page dynamically using JavaScript.

// example of DOM manipulation:
const heading = document.getElementById("heading");
heading.textContent = "Hello, World!";

// in this example, we are selecting an element with the id "heading" and changing its text content to "Hello, World!" using the textContent property. 
// This is just one example of how we can manipulate the DOM using JavaScript. There are many other methods and properties available for working with the DOM, such as createElement(), appendChild(), removeChild(), and more.
//meaning in punjabi, DOM nu "Document Object Model" keh sakde haan, te eh web documents di structure nu represent karda hai.   

